quizzes.question:
Type in a code to declare a variable x, assign it to value 4 + 6, and print it to the screen.
[!raw!]
int {0};
x = 4 + 6;
{1} << x {2} endl;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Arithmetic Operators[/h1]

C++ supports these arithmetic operators. [img id="2449" width="100%"]
The addition operator adds its operands together.[code format="cpp" codeId="182"]int x = 40 + 60;
cout << x;

// Outputs [b]100[/b][/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the missing parts in the following code to print 12.
[!raw!]
int x = 24;
int y;
y = {0} - 12;
cout << {1} << endl;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Subtraction[/h1]

The subtraction operator subtracts one operand from the other.[code format="cpp" codeId="183"]int x = 100 - 60;
cout << x;

//Outputs [b]40[/b][/code]

[h1]Multiplication[/h1]

The multiplication operator multiplies its operands.[code format="cpp" codeId="184"]int x = 5 * 6;
cout << x;

//Outputs [b]30[/b][/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to declare variable x and assign it the value 81 divided by 3:
[!raw!]
int {0} = 81 {1} 3;
cout << x;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Division[/h1]

The division operator divides the first operand by the second. Any remainder is dropped in order to return an integer value.
[b]Example: [/b][code format="cpp" codeId="185"]int x = 10 / 3;
cout << x;

// Outputs [b]3[/b][/code]
If one or both of the operands are floating point values, the division operator performs floating point division. 
[note]Dividing by 0 will crash your program.[/note]

[h1]Modulus[/h1]

The modulus operator (%) is informally known as the remainder operator because it returns the remainder after an integer division. 

[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="186"]int x = 25 % 7;
cout << x;

// Outputs [b]4[/b][/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the missing parentheses to have x's value equal 14.
[!raw!]
int x = {0} 4 + 3 {1} * 2;
cout << x;

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Operator Precedence[/h1]

Operator [b]precedence [/b]determines the grouping of terms in an expression, which affects how an expression is evaluated. Certain operators take higher precedence over others; for example, the multiplication operator has higher precedence over the addition operator.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cpp" codeId="187"]int x = 5+2*2;
cout << x;
// Outputs [b]9[/b][/code]
The program evaluates 2*2 first, and then adds the result to 5.
As in mathematics, using [b]parentheses [/b]alters operator precedence. [code format="cpp" codeId="188"]int x = (5 + 2) *2;
cout << x;

// Outputs 14[/code]
